TY  - JOUR
AU  - Dávila, Eduardo
AU  - Hébert, Benjamin
T1  - Optimal Corporate Taxation Under Financial Frictions
PY  - 2023
Y1  - 2023/07/01
DO  - 10.1093/restud/rdac068
JO  - The Review of Economic Studies
JA  - Rev Econ Stud
VL  - 90
IS  - 4
SP  - 1893
EP  - 1933
SN  - 0034-6527
AB  - This article studies the optimal design of corporate taxes when firms have private information about future investment opportunities and face financial constraints. A government whose goal is to efficiently raise a given amount of revenue from its corporate sector should attempt to tax unconstrained firms, which value resources inside the firm less than financially constrained firms. We show that a corporate payout tax (a tax on dividends and share repurchases) can both separate constrained and unconstrained firms and raise revenue and is therefore optimal. Our quantitative analysis implies that a revenue-neutral switch from profit taxation to payout taxation would increase the overall value of existing firms and new entrants by $7\%$. This switch could be implemented in the current US tax system by making retained earnings fully deductible.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/restud/rdac068
ER  - 



